&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;I have a very sensitive old AM tuner with a flywheel tuning
&gt; &gt; &gt;system. I tried
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;several recording sessions manually sweeping the tuner through the
&gt; &gt; &gt;AM band
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;late at night. I got pretty good at keeping the dial moving at a
&gt; &gt; &gt;constant
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;rate of speed. This is not nearly as good as Frank&#39;s &#39;hands off&#39;
&gt; &gt; &gt;random
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;tuning method but it still produced some results. What impressed
&gt; &gt; &gt;me most is
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;that some of the voices sound the same, even though I tuned
&gt; &gt; &gt;through several
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;channels. This attached capture could be a technical message.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;&quot;Plug a million hertz&quot;   One Million Hertz = 1mhz = 1000khz, which
&gt; &gt; &gt;is close
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;the center frequency for the AM broadcast band.
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;Dave
